http://www.avn.info.ve/contenido/rayuela-50-years-eternal-youth^Rayuela, 50 years of eternal youth | AVN^NA^20130723095031^0.07530785^b5cc619e22539aa7346f6a2354576a7d^0.030013459^2013-07-23T13:57:22.487Z^http://www.avn.info.ve/contenido/rayuela-50-years-eternal-youth^"Rayuela, 50 years of eternal youth | AVN Special Reports Rayuela, 50 years of eternal youth por Raúl Cazal “I'd like it to be my official photo. I'd like it to be someday in one of my book covers,” Julio Cortázar, 1967. Picture: Sara Facio. Caracas, 21 Jun. AVN.- Hopscotch is still played at school or in the streets. It's just enough to have a piece of chalk, a bit of good shot and balance. Time goes by and it is still played, the same as Julio Cortázar's Rayuela (or Hopscotch) which 50 years after being released at bookstores in Buenos Aires, continues being read by young people anywhere in the world. It's like if the book was released for the first time, said the Great Cronopio a year before his death, at an interview with El Juglar bookstore, in Mexico, 1983. When he wrote the novel, Cortázar thought he was making it for his generation, though this did not understand the book's ludic essence. His stories and philosophical digressions were aimed at later generations. First criticism, naturally on their behalf, who declared to newspapers, was very negative. They attacked the book fiercely. And in that moment it was read by the young and there it found, maybe, its final destination, which continues so along two decades. So, it is for me an admirable reward. Writer Cristina Peri Rossi, talking about Cortázar, always does it in present time and she affirms that among writers of the so-called Latin American boom, he was the most loved by readers and the one writers of the next generation identified with easier. Any of great writers would become a classic then: Jorge Luis Borges, Alejo Carpentier, Peri Rossi says; Julio Cortázar, in turn, would never stop being young, anti-bourgeois, sniper, reader's accomplice, a player, without stopping to be, at the same time, a great reader, a cultured writer, lover of painting, music and literature called 'minor'. I like better writers called minor than great, Cristina. Because a great writer, a Shakespeare or a Cervantes, does not inspire: they are there, perfect, they may be just admired. Whereas how many good ideas are in minor writers, how many advantageous failures; a minor writer always may be corrected, but not a great one, Cortázar wrote to her. The game as an invitation to read is crucial aspect in his literature: he is loved because of that game, Peri Rossi recalls, but also due to his lack of solemnity, his irreverent behavior in the face of the Academy's linguistic norms, his rebelliousness, his reformist and iconoclast spirit. Narrative monument Mario Goloboff says, in Julio Cortázar: la biografia , that Rayuela is something more than a recent and close novel, a text that was there, together with its author and with us, appealing us from its originality and modernity, it may be estimated, without exaggeration, as one of Latin America's narrative monument in the (20th) century. Contemporaneously, there was an impression about that something was happening with Rayuela 's new narrative language and that there was a certain epic and lyric slipping, and the oral field going to writing in the novel, or rather, Rayuela was helping to produce. Modesty, humbleness accompanied Cortázar, as well as perspicacity to see the other side of things and facts, to place them in other perspective without thinking of himself as an intellectual, but just for the simple pleasure of taking time over thinking, painting or music, and finding the invisible fabric that halts every piece observed inside his fiftyish novel. The initial warning the author brings up in ludic form – Rayuela consists of many books, but two books above all– is in part a reconsideration of literature, an explicit attempt to raise the reader's complicity, to make him stop being passive. The game is complete, so that literature, through itself, moves its foundations. He had been writing the novel for a year and, in a letter dated in Paris, 27 June 1959, he explains to Jean Bernabé – who traduced his short stories into French – that he likes novels less and less, the way novels are made nowadays. What I'm writing now will be (if I ever get to finish it) something like an anti-novel, an attempt to break patterns in which that genre is petrified. I think 'psychological' novels have come to an end and if we should continue writing worthy things, then we have to start a different direction. Eventually, Cortázar would change his mind about calling Rayuela an anti-novel. before promoting the book, he said he would not like an emphasis in this book's side of 'novel', as it could be read in a letter he sent to Francisco Porrúa, Sudamericana editor on 5 January 1963. It would be like defrauding readers. I know it is also a novel and that in the end, perhaps it is its side of novel which is worth. But I have already written it as counter-novel. From the other side Four years took Cortázar to write Rayuela , between 1958 and 1962. During that term, there appeared in Latin America pieces like Guerra del Tiempo (1958) and El siglo de las luces (1962), by Alejo Carpentier; La región más transparente (1958), La muerte de Artemio Cruz and Aura (1962), by Carlos Fuentes; Montevideanos (1959) and La tregua (1969), by Mario Benedetti; Los pequeños seres (1959) and Los habitantes (1961), by Salvador Garmendia; El hacedor (1969), by Jorge Luis Borges; Hijo del hombre (1969), by Augusto Roa Bastos; El coronel no tiene quien le escriba (1961), Los funerales de la Mamá Grande and La mala hora (1962), by Gabriel García Márquez; El astillero (1961), by Juan Carlos Onetti; Oficina No. 1 (1961), by Miguel Otero Silva; and Bomarzo (1962), by Manuel Mujica Láinez. Cortázar had been working on Rayuela for a year when he wrote to Bernabé: If I continued writing fantastic short stories I would feel like a swindler; modesty aside, I already find it too easy. Subsequently, in letters, interviews or while doing the dishes, he confessed that if he did not write it he would had thrown himself to Seine. When he got the first view from Argentina of the second reader of this book, Paco Porrúa, he told the first reader, his wife Aurora Bernárdez, in Paris: Now I may die, since there is a man who has felt what I needed the reader to feel. Los reyes is the first book published under his name, in 1949; eleven years before appeared one of poems, Presencia , under the pseudonym Julio Denis, written with a view to have his friends as the only readers. Talking with Ernesto González Bermejo, he said he delayed in publishing the book so much due to severity; a tremendous self-criticism. Then followed short stories Bestiario , 1951; Final del Juego , 1956; and Las armas secretas , 1959. In the latter book appears El perseguidor , estimated by some critics as nouveau, a kind of rupture in his style though never abandoning fiction. Cortázar himself estimated this story as a sort of little Rayuela and confessed in Salvo el crepúsculo (1984) that a friend had advised him to destroy it. In El perseguidor , I wanted to quit to all kind of intervention and to be inside my own personal territory, it is to say, look somehow at myself. And looking at myself meant looking at men, looking also at a fellow-man. I had looked very little to the human genre until I wrote El perseguidor . Vanity rather than easiness In 1960, Julio Cortázar published his first novel, Los premios , though he had already burnt another of about 600 pages. It was a very sentimental novel, but there were some very dramatic and extreme situations, long discussions, whose solutions I would like to know today. I have nothing but a general idea, he said to González Bermejo. There were also relegated to oblivion two short novels, some essays, a lot of texts – and plenty of poems, but that is another chapter. A young boy, under conditions of Argentineans of that time, who rushed too much to publish, refusing to do it, proves rather a great vanity or great vigor. I really prefer to be too vain than acting flippantly. While creating stories of Horacio Oliveira and La Maga, his books appeared in other areas far from Argentina. His short stories were translated and published in magazines and anthologies, in which he had to remain firm so that editors would not mutilate his texts. I know very well that my short story [ Casa tomada ] is too long for the magazine, he wrote to Americas' editor Kathleen Walker. But when a tailor tries a suit which does not fit me, he would not think of asking me to cut my legs or reduce to five the total number of ribs. Similarly, a seller of painting frames would not intend the painter to suppress several centimeters of his canvas so that it fits exactly the available model. In this case, the frame is Americas and if my short story is really so worth to be published, as you say in the last phrase of your letter, the frame should suit the canvass, not the other way. Otherwise, it would be perhaps excellent journalism; but we know that from good journalism comes bad literature. Along the same lines, he disagreed with Roger Callois, who had selected La noche boca arriba for an anthology to be published by Gallimard. The risk of your short story, Cortázar recalls the words from the French writer and literary critic, is that French readers may think that it is just about the hallucination of a man who was operated... Don't you think that it would be better to add a final phrase, for instance, that the following day nurses found the patient dead, and looking at him they realized that there was a wound at his chest and that his heart was missing? Great questions Paco Porrúa, by the mid of 1962, received Rayuela 's handwritten copy. In turn, Cortázar received copies of the first edition of Historias de cronopios y de famas . Always doubting about what he was writing, because everything started by gathering papers, pieces of novel, and Cortázar himself could not realize that he was writing a novel. Chapters were accumulating. When I went back and started to write the part of Paris, I made a first narrative chapter, then some small chapters loose – where La Maga appears incidentally and initial more or less magic encounters – and then a very, very long chapter where characters start shaping. He did not expected to send the handwritten copy to Sudamericana either, since he could not imagine the publisher releasing that. They will be dreadfully disappointed, this Cortázar that was doing so well..., he wrote to Porrúa in a letter on August 14, 1961. As soon as the editor read the 600-pages handwritten copy, he wrote: My first reaction is to throw the book to your head, and Cortázar replied: That is what I'm waiting for. In that moment, Porrúa, who become his close friend, recognized that Rayuela was a novel the wrong way round from all conventions and traditions, not only because of its structure but also its ease language. Biographer and writer Mario Goloboff affirms that a summary of the plot may start by saying that it is the story of an Argentinean exiled in Paris, Horacio Oliveira, his homesickness, difficulties, troubles and social, human and erotic experiences. Cortázar would summarize it personally at an interview with Margarita Garcia Flores:  Rayuela is somehow like a summary of my ten years in Paris, plus previous years. There, I made the strongest attempt I was able to do in that moment to try in terms of novels what others, philosophers, try in metaphysical terms. I mean, great queries, great questions. He was in search of an accomplice reader. In chapters about Berthe Trépat's concert or Rocamadour's death, he allowed to be carried by a narration which grew until reaching a fictional kind of hypnotist dimension. So, at the end of those chapters, or in the mid of those chapters, it is inserted a notice, a small theoretic comment which has apparently nothing to do with it, just to wash the reader's face. That is the idea. To tell him: 'do not be carried by so many emotions'. Eternal youth Julio Cortázar left Argentina without understanding the historic moment, more concerned about his bourgeois condition and, in Paris, writing Rayuela , he starts realizing, though without being aware that the outcome may not be individual, as character Oliveira stands out in several moments. Without all that Rayuela involves, I wouldn't had been able to take that step that took me abruptly to find out, with the coagulant eye that meant the Cuban Revolution, a Latin America which, as such, I couldn't care less up till then. I would not care but about individuals, about values which had a meaning for me and an aesthetic universe. According to Cortázar, language that tells a story is that which opens windows to reality; a permanent opening of holes at men's wall, which comes between ourselves and the rest. In June1963 appears Rayuela and by the end of that year he travels to Cuba. Since that moment, his name would be tied to revolution, socialism, as it also is the aesthetic, his books' complicity with readers and the literary game. Magas feel portrayed and seduced reading it, cronopios find famas and go away or make fun of them. Because of this and many other things, Cortázar was always young, he never stopped being young. So is Rayuela . &nbsp; Translation by AVN Raúl Cazal AVN 21/06/2013 09:47 Special Reports Mandela's long walk Special Reports AH1N1 or media interests over health care Special Reports The Face of Hatred Special Reports Mandela's long walk Rayuela, 50 years of eternal youth Headlines 17.00 Maduro and Santos meet in Puerto Ayacucho 16.36 Meeting between Maduro and Santos to resume bilateral agenda 14.33 Movements marched to eradicate hunger, poverty 12.53 We aim to structurally reduce crime by 40% by 2019 12.37 Meeting of CELAC ministers starts in 