http://www.avn.info.ve/contenido/ah1n1-or-media-interests-over-health-care^AH1N1 or media interests over health care | AVN^NA^20130723194309^0.011766853^5ee0ab852e4445c88ebbbe92db7ded4e^0.0052457866^2013-07-24T00:10:32.761Z^http://www.avn.info.ve/contenido/ah1n1-or-media-interests-over-health-care^"AH1N1 or media interests over health care | AVN Special Reports AH1N1 or media interests over health care &nbsp; Caracas, 29 May. AVN.- The shortage of vaccines and face masks reported at front pages of Venezuela's three main newspapers (El Nacional, El Universal and Ultimas Noticias) raises alarms and also the tinkling of cash registers at drugstores. It is not weird to read outbreak and threat of pandemic in national media when influenza AH1N1 has become news again, after the 2009 global pandemic. While El Nacional's edition on May 28 reports 400 cases of contagion registered in the country, for El Universal and Ultimas Noticias the figure is about 200. But there is one common aspect under penalty of data inconsistencies: launching a campaign based on fear and the media strategy of, as Health minister Isabel Iturria said, making believe that we will all die of influenza. Right on May 28, journalist and media analyst Alfredo Oliva claimed in local television that there is a climate in which people struggle to position perceptions, it is to say, a moment in which political battle brewing in a perceptive position. There is a battle for perception. I mean, there is a perception of terror, fear, set up through the media... You may ask any Venezuelan today: You who watch television and watch the news in private television, is there any news which does not start with a catastrophe or a violent event? And when there is not, it is invented that a little cat anywhere was hanging up at high-voltage cables and a woman fell down trying to rescue the little cat. Why? Because what they need is to create tragic scenarios and violence to continue exacerbating that perception and set up the perception of a Venezuela where you cannot live, Oliva said in the interview. Figures of casualties and suspicious cases accompany bright headlines such as Vaccines and face masks vanish (Ultimas Noticias, Tuesday 28 may) and AH1N1 caused 17 casualties (El Nacional, May 28), not failing to denounce the alleged absence of a public health policy which would had made possible to prevent current influenza cases. Meanwhile, expert Rafael Uribe is quoted at El Nacional blaming the Venezuelan State for the quick and sustained spread of that virus because necessary measures were not taken when the outbreak started, Health minister Isabel Iturria affirmed at private TV station Globovision that the National Government has a policy to vaccinate against influenza and about four million people in risk have been vaccinated annually: people who suffer cardiovascular diseases with heart failure, chronic obstructive bronchopulmonary disease, general severe lung diseases, diabetic, people suffering cancer, pregnant in the second and third quarter. Viral immunization is contraindicated for children under 11 months. In the case of Venezuela, there is an immunization program which includes vaccines against influenza, vaccines prior influenza, which includes subtype H1N1 since the year 2010. It is to say, in the last three consecutive years, influenza vaccine has been present in Venezuela's immunization system and four million have been applied since the year 2011, over three million doses of influenza vaccine in this term 2012 up to 2013 -which has finished- and influenza vaccine is addressed specifically to certain groups, minister Iturria said. But the media cares a little about this information, casualty figures – crucial maxim at sensationalism – they seem to call more on people's attention. So much that Dr Iturria, also Public Health expert, was compelled to insist on explaining that the best information may be that addressed to prevention, not to spread paranoia among the population. As a matter of fact, Iturria said that alarmed people and pseudo-scientific information may lead to contraproductive behavior to prevent contagion, while face masks and vaccines start to be scarce. Together with implicit wake-up calls ride the strategy of making invisible the global scale of that virus, making seem as strictly local a public health problem that, as a result of a series of diseases such as severe respiratory infections, is spread across the world. Vaccines, necessary? During her interview at Globovision, Dr Iturria emphasized that the AH1N1 vaccine is not the most important measure for prevention. The most important measure, I repeat, is washing our hands, people with influenza symptoms should stay at home and no way vaccination. Like her, other experts quoted in small comments in the local media, such as infectious disease expert Julio Castro, who explained to Ultimas Noticias that a doses against AH1N1 influenza will not allow to control the current situation since it starts protecting people three weeks after its injection. Nevertheless, pictures at front pages continue showing people being vaccinated and long queues at vaccination centers. In the face of a fierce media campaign, minister Iturria emphasized that the issue of immunization is also managed inappropriately and then what we cause again is more panic and more search of something that is not the real solution. The preventive measure is more relevant and I repeat it, it is washing our hands. The appropriate way to prevent the spread of Flugge droplets, drops of saliva when we cough and sneeze is protecting the mouth with the elbow instead of the hand. And immunization is expected for certain particular groups according to domestic standards. Abiding by those domestic standards, there must be exclusively vaccinated those who have already been vaccinated. Those who have not been vaccinated must wait for the new doses against influenza in the year 2013-2014, whose launching is expected for the last quarter of the year. Its implementation was carried out in the Latin American seasonal, which embraces months of March, April and May. About getting the flu vaccine in the corresponding term (first and last quarter of the year) -instead of a mass vaccination campaign – it results really effective to protect from the virus. Vaccinating out of time may on the contrary give patients the believe that he is completely protected and he may be exposing to the virus without being immunized. About face masks Information without scientific basis and filled with political interests may act severely against halting the problem and preserving health. That is the case of the use of face masks, crucial piece in news of private newspapers which, without exception, alert about their shortage. According to Iturria, this is only result of paranoia and it does not have any scientific ground. Using face masks may only increase the risk of people getting the virus if it is used inappropriately. Face mask is not devised for protection, it is not planned for a healthy person to protect from a virus; on the contrary, it is devised for a sick person not to spread Flugge droplets with his saliva when he talks, or coughing, or sneezing, not to spread viral particles to the environment, which drop on surfaces and remain feasible for 10, 12 hours, depending on the environment. The probability that a healthy person takes the face mask without washing his hands and placing the virus in the surface of th face mask, which then comes back to his face, close to his nasal mucus, eyes and mouth does nothing but multiplying the risk of the person being affected by the virus. The use of face masks is absolutely out of context and it is the result of what I call paranoia, what I call people's confusion in which sometimes an information is given inadequately, plus death throes of the media's management on the 2009 pandemic, added the Minister. Careful information The information people must receive in matters of health, when treated inadequately, causes inadequate behavior among the population, affirmed Health minister Isabel Iturria. Her words seem to be a graphic reflect of pictures of national media. In this connection, she rejected the war report-style treatment given by the media to a public health problem that, precisely given the risk it entails, should be prevented pedagogically to inform the population about necessary preventive measures, instead of the number of casualties, as it dealt with news relating to the page of crime reports. If you give, for instance, information everyday about the war report and then write in big, thick and red letters at the front page 'Vaccines and face masks are over,' the message you give to the population is 'Start running to see if you find a face mask or find immediately someone with a vaccine.' And from the public health perspective that message is completely wrong. If you interview anyone here, regardless of their political leaning, member of the Government or not, he may say the same, that it is absurd to use face masks on healthy population, he must say even the way a clearly opponent person said, and that is the president of the Society of Scientific Societies, that washing the hands is more important than immunization. A matter of perception, analyst Alfredo Oliva would say, but while the media raise every time more as a battle scenario that not for being symbolic stops generating concrete realities, outside newspapers, outside TV screens and radio stations, there is an even more important battle to carry out, that of providing the needed information to fight the battle for life and preserve health. AVN 29/05/2013 15:36 Special Reports Mandela's long walk Special Reports Rayuela, 50 years of eternal youth Special Reports The Face of Hatred Special Reports Mandela's long walk Rayuela, 50 years of eternal youth Headlines 17.09 System of Food Mission will continue to strengthen 15.26 New food plant to process six tons of meat per day 13.55 Venezuelan FM demands US to respect the country's sovereignty 13.47 Maduro opened food complex in Monagas 13.31 Venezuela deepens strategic relationship with China See more Noticias Multimedia SIBCI ULAN Aliados Poder Popular Caracas Fotografía Correo del Orinoco ANTV ABI Prensa Latina IRNA Gestión Social Regiones Video La Radio del Sur Avila TV Agencia Brasil Telam VNA Política Internacionales Radio Radio Mundial Telesur AGN Xinhua Economía Reportajes RNV TVES Andes Educación Opinión VIVE IP Paraguay Cultura Archivo VTV Notimex Deportes English Agencia Venezolana de Noticias Torre Lincoln, Piso 7, Sabana Grande, Caracas - Venezuela - Teléfono: +58 212-781-2711 Servicios Contáctenos"
http://www.avn.info.ve/contenido/venezolanos-se-comprometen-erradicaci%C3%B3n-del-hambre-y-pobreza^Venezolanos se comprometen con la erradicación del hambre y la pobreza | AVN^NA^20130723194309^0.011766853^73b62802c5298aa1c527cc11a5572b08^0.0056244275^2013-07-23T23:57:45.016Z^http://www.avn.info.ve/contenido/venezolanos-se-comprometen-erradicaci%C3%B3n-del-hambre-y-pobreza^"Venezolanos se comprometen con la erradicación del hambre y la pobreza | AVN CELAC 2013 Venezolanos se comprometen con la erradicación del hambre y la pobreza &nbsp; Caracas, 22 Jul. AVN.- Países que conforma la Comunidad de Estados Latinoamericanos y Caribeños (Celac) suman voluntades para llevar a cero los niveles del hambre y la pobreza en la Región y el pueblo venezolano también está comprometido a alcanzar dicho objetivo. Zaida Cartaya, del estado Trujillo, entidad de los Andes venezolanos,&nbsp;dijo que con el trabajo permanente, consciente y solidario se puede lograr. Todos debemos asumir, como ciudadanos, ese trabajo. Tenemos que trabajar para un fin colectivo: el mejor bienestar para el pueblo. Adiós al egoísmo, a las individualidades. Tenemos que ser (Hugo) Chávez, elevar su nombre a lo más alto, manifestó Zaida, en referencia al líder de la Revolución Bolivariana y quien recibe de los venezolanos el título de Redentor de los pobres. Comentó que el Comandante Supremo dedicó gran parte de su vida a la búsqueda de la felicidad de su pueblo, a erradicar las desigualdades de todo tipo. Lograr una América Latina bonita, donde no haya ni una familia en condición de pobreza extrema sería un tributo a su nombre, agregó esta trujillana con toda convicción. Zaida Cartaya participó junto a otros venezolanos en la marcha que tuvo como destino la Plaza Sucre, donde se ubica el Teatro Catia, sitio de encuentro para los ministros del área social de los países miembros de la Celac. Debe revisarse el uso de transgénicos Micaela Raya, de Argentina, manifestó que el encuentro de los ministros este lunes y martes representa un importante avance por la integración. Al ser entrevistada por la periodista de Venezolana de Televisión, Micaela indicó que la reunión es un buen síntoma porque lo que allí se discutirá para erradicar el hambre podrá ser expandido en el continente. Propone que para hacer más sólida la soberanía alimentaria debe revisarse el uso de transgénicos en la agricultura, para garantizar que sean los productores, con sus técnicas e insumos, los que produzcan sanos alimentos. Por su parte, Liliana Betancourt y Yuraima Gutiérrez, de la Misión Madres del Barrio, programa que promueve el financiamiento de proyectos socioproductivos en las mujeres más pobres, manifestaron que programas sociales como esta misión son necesarios para erradicar la pobreza. Por la erradicación del hambre y la pobreza es el lema de esta reunión que se mantendrá hasta este martes 22 de julio y donde se discutirán tres temas específicos: educación, alimentación y salud. En paralelo, representantes de los movimientos sociales de los diferentes países de la Celac también se reunirán para exponer sus aportes y transmitirlos a los respectivos gobiernos. Las conclusiones de este encuentro serán entregadas a los ministros del área social de la Celac para que incluyan las propuestas de los movimientos sociales en su declaración final, que será elevada posteriormente para la consideración de los presidentes del organismo. AVN 22/07/2013 14:27 CELAC 2013 Venezuela insiste en la necesidad de sistematizar experiencias regionales de inclusión social CELAC 2013 Generación de empleos productivos es punto central en reunión ministerial de la CELAC CELAC 2013 Venezuela propone crear programas de educación, salud y alimentación de la Celac Opinión Mercosur y el sueño consciente de un visionario por Isabel Cristina Delgado Arria Egipto: otro eslabón del fracaso de la maniobra contra Siria por Sergio Rodríguez Gelfenstein Reportajes El fascismo en el triunfo del horror por Raúl Cazal Datagate se inició